00:39:13,611 --> 00:39:16,531
Way down there with the man.

513
00:39:16,651 --> 00:39:18,651
The mean man.

514
00:39:21,931 --> 00:39:23,811
What is that man doing?

515
00:39:23,931 --> 00:39:25,971
Trying to get up.

516
00:39:26,091 --> 00:39:29,011
Trying to get up into our world.

517
00:39:58,651 --> 00:40:00,491
Where's Daddy now?

518
00:40:06,611 --> 00:40:08,131
Daddy's in heaven.

519
00:40:10,011 --> 00:40:11,931
He's with God now.

520
00:40:14,851 --> 00:40:18,931
Do you have to die to see God?

521
00:40:19,051 --> 00:40:20,611
I don't think so.

522
00:40:23,931 --> 00:40:25,531
I think you have to pray.

523
00:40:28,491 --> 00:40:30,131
And reach out.

524
00:40:34,851 --> 00:40:37,971
Why does God let there
be bad things?

525
00:40:41,211 --> 00:40:43,531
I honestly don't know, honey.

526
00:40:46,611 --> 00:40:48,451
Please try to get some sleep.

527
00:40:58,171 --> 00:41:00,611
Can you come with me
in my dreams?

528
00:41:04,971 --> 00:41:07,451
I think that only
happens in the movies.

529
00:41:09,771 --> 00:41:12,811
But I'll always, always...

530
00:41:12,931 --> 00:41:15,051
be right here when you get back.

531
00:41:17,171 --> 00:41:22,691
And I'll make sure
that nobody gets your toes.

532
00:42:10,571 --> 00:42:13,491
I know his behaviour
is bizarre...

533
00:42:13,611 --> 00:42:16,011
but he's usually so normal
and well adjusted, John...

534
00:42:16,131 --> 00:42:17,171
I can't believe it's him...

535
00:42:17,291 --> 00:42:19,971
and not something outside
influencing him.

536
00:42:21,131 --> 00:42:23,291
Or is that how denial works?

537
00:42:24,411 --> 00:42:25,611
It is denial.

538
00:42:25,731 --> 00:42:28,251
I don't think
that's the case here.

539
00:42:28,371 --> 00:42:29,891
If you're really worried
about Dylan...

540
00:42:30,011 --> 00:42:31,851
have a doctor check him out.

541
00:42:31,971 --> 00:42:33,411
You'll see. Everything's fine.

542
00:42:33,531 --> 00:42:37,091
You're not just saying that
to help a crazy friend cope?

543
00:42:39,011 --> 00:42:41,491
Everything about Dylan's
behaviour is understandable...

544
00:42:41,611 --> 00:42:44,571
for a kid
who just lost his father.

545
00:42:44,691 --> 00:42:48,011
How does a child
process a thing like that?

546
00:42:48,131 --> 00:42:49,571
I don't know.

547
00:42:51,011 --> 00:42:53,811
I've not been able
to process it very well myself.

548
00:42:53,931 --> 00:42:56,571
And you're not crazy,
by the way.

549
00:42:56,691 --> 00:43:00,011
Seeing Freddy in that grave
and then jumping in...

550
00:43:00,131 --> 00:43:01,171
you didn't jump in.

551
00:43:01,291 --> 00:43:04,211
That's my memory.
It seemed absolutely real.

552
00:43:04,331 --> 00:43:05,651
"Seemed," not "was."

553
00:43:08,771 --> 00:43:11,531
It's in my family, you know.

554
00:43:11,651 --> 00:43:13,491
What is?

555
00:43:13,611 --> 00:43:16,451
A very close relative
died in an institution.

556
00:43:16,571 --> 00:43:20,651
Really? If having a screwy
family made a person crazy...

557
00:43:21,531 --> 00:43:23,771
the whole world
would be one big loony bin.

558
00:43:26,571 --> 00:43:28,931
You have a crazed fan after you.

559
00:43:29,051 --> 00:43:32,291
That's what's making you crazy.
Probably Dylan, too.

560
00:43:32,411 --> 00:43:33,891
I never mentioned that to him.

561
00:43:34,011 --> 00:43:37,011
Kids know when something's
bugging the parent.

562
00:43:38,531 --> 00:43:41,651
You have no idea
who this is calling?

563
00:43:41,771 --> 00:43:44,251
- Freddy, for all I know.
- Come on.

564
00:43:44,931 --> 00:43:46,331
He's a man.

565
00:43:47,491 --> 00:43:52,251
Or a boy
with a deep Freddy voice.

566
00:43:52,371 --> 00:43:55,611
Six weeks, and you're surprised
you got Freddy in your dreams?

567
00:43:55,731 --> 00:43:57,931
Hell, Sonny Bono,
after a while...

568
00:43:58,051 --> 00:44:01,051
began seeing his stalker
everywhere, even at Mass.

569
00:44:01,171 --> 00:44:02,211
Really?

570
00:44:03,171 --> 00:44:05,731
How many times
did Letterman call the cops...

571
00:44:05,851 --> 00:44:08,251
thinking that woman
was down in the kitchen again?

572
00:44:09,651 --> 00:44:13,411
Really gets under your skin
if you let it.

573
00:44:18,131 --> 00:44:19,731
You really think Dylan's OK?

574
00:44:19,851 --> 00:44:22,971
Dylan's fine. You're fine.

575
00:44:23,091 --> 00:44:24,971
You're hurting,
but you're fine...

576
00:44:25,091 --> 00:44:26,651
and you're definitely not crazy.

577
00:44:27,411 --> 00:44:28,931
My worst fear...

578
00:44:29,771 --> 00:44:33,251
that whatever madness
is in my family I have...

579
00:44:43,011 --> 00:44:44,931
and I've passed it onto Dylan.

580
00:45:03,011 --> 00:45:05,811
- Make sure he's OK, John.
- Are you all right?

581
00:45:05,931 --> 00:45:08,331
Are you OK? Are you sure?
Does anything hurt?

582
00:45:08,451 --> 00:45:10,051
Dylan, are you all right?

583
00:45:10,171 --> 00:45:13,371
Honey, are you all right?
Are you sure?

584
00:45:13,491 --> 00:45:15,731
God wouldn't take me.

585
00:45:18,251 --> 00:45:20,291
Oh, my God. Oh, honey.

586
00:45:20,411 --> 00:45:21,811
It's unbelievable.

587
00:46:17,571 --> 00:46:20,131
- You doing all right?
- Hanging in there.

588
00:46:20,291 --> 00:46:22,171
You know the guy that was
calling me all the time?

589
00:46:22,331 --> 00:46:23,571
He started again...

590
00:46:23,731 --> 00:46:25,531
and he's putting stuff
in my mail again.

591
00:46:25,691 --> 00:46:28,251
Listen, the S.O.B. Probably
read about the funeral...

592
00:46:28,371 --> 00:46:29,571
in the papers or something.

593
00:46:29,731 --> 00:46:31,811
Sick mother.

594
00:46:31,971 --> 00:46:34,371
That's the last thing
you need right now, I'm sure.

595
00:46:34,531 --> 00:46:37,731
Actually, it's been giving me
Freddy nightmares.

596
00:46:37,891 --> 00:46:40,051
Wait a second.
Now, let me get this straight.

597
00:46:40,211 --> 00:46:43,851
You're having nightmares
about Freddy? As in me?

598
00:46:44,011 --> 00:46:47,971
No. It isn't you. He's scarier.

599
00:46:49,771 --> 00:46:50,731
He's...

600
00:46:51,651 --> 00:46:52,691
Darker?

601
00:46:53,771 --> 00:46:54,731
More evil?

602
00:46:54,891 --> 00:46:57,851
Yeah. How did you know?

603
00:46:57,971 --> 00:46:59,771
Call it a guess.

604
00:46:59,931 --> 00:47:01,811
Pretty damn good guess.

605
00:47:02,891 --> 00:47:05,211
Anyway
what I was calling about was...

606
00:47:05,371 --> 00:47:07,491
have you seen any of the script
by any chance?

607
00:47:07,651 --> 00:47:11,091
No. Wes won't show it
until he's finished.

608
00:47:11,251 --> 00:47:12,651
At least that's what he told me.

609
00:47:12,811 --> 00:47:14,011
When is it gonna be done?

610
00:47:14,171 --> 00:47:17,131
The way he's writing, who knows?

611
00:47:17,251 --> 00:47:19,131
It's so weird.

612
00:47:19,251 --> 00:47:20,971
I asked him how far
he was at the funeral.

613
00:47:21,091 --> 00:47:23,211
What did he say? Oh, yeah.

614
00:47:23,331 --> 00:47:26,131
"As far as Dylan
trying to reach God."

615
00:47:26,291 --> 00:47:29,091
Whatever that means. Weird, huh?

616
00:47:29,251 --> 00:47:31,811
Putting your kid in the script.

617
00:47:31,931 --> 00:47:35,891
Robert...
have you been having nightmares?

618
00:47:39,971 --> 00:47:42,251
Look, we need to talk,
but not over the phone.

619
00:47:42,371 --> 00:47:44,251
Can I come over?

620
00:47:44,371 --> 00:47:49,131
Actually, Heather...
today's no good.

621
00:47:49,291 --> 00:47:52,971
There's something
I have to finish.

622
00:47:53,131 --> 00:47:54,411
Tomorrow maybe, huh?

623
00:47:54,531 --> 00:47:57,571
OK, tomorrow.
But early in the morning.

624
00:47:57,691 --> 00:48:00,131
And meanwhile, Robert,
take care, OK?

625
00:48:01,131 --> 00:48:03,411
Yeah. Sure.

626
00:50:22,822 --> 00:50:23,822
Damn it!

627
00:50:38,542 --> 00:50:43,782
One, two,
Freddy's coming for you!

628
00:50:52,662 --> 00:50:56,702
Three, four,
better lock your door

629
00:51:00,702 --> 00:51:04,822
Five, six, grab your crucifix

630
00:51:07,942 --> 00:51:12,102
Seven, eight,
better stay up late

631
00:51:13,302 --> 00:51:16,182
Dylan, don't sing that song.

632
00:51:17,822 --> 00:51:22,022
Nine, ten, never sleep again!

633
00:51:25,342 --> 00:51:27,502
Dylan! Stop it!

634
00:51:28,302 --> 00:51:29,982
No! Don't!

635
00:51:34,262 --> 00:51:36,342
Never sleep again

636
00:51:36,462 --> 00:51:39,982
Never sleep again

637
00:51:40,102 --> 00:51:43,062
Never sleep again

638
00:51:43,182 --> 00:51:45,702
Never sleep again

639
00:52:24,782 --> 00:52:25,822
I touched him.

640
00:52:53,862 --> 00:52:56,062
Any history of epilepsy
in your family?

641
00:52:57,582 --> 00:52:58,622
Diabetes?

642
00:53:00,302 --> 00:53:04,342
Was there a trigger event,
trauma, shock?

643
00:53:04,462 --> 00:53:07,782
You haven't shown him
the films you've made, have you?

644
00:53:07,902 --> 00:53:09,382
The horror stuff?

645
00:53:09,502 --> 00:53:11,822
His father just passed away.

646
00:53:11,942 --> 00:53:13,902
I'm sorry.

647
00:53:14,862 --> 00:53:18,382
But I'm convinced
those films can tip...

648
00:53:18,502 --> 00:53:20,942
an unstable child over the edge.

649
00:53:21,062 --> 00:53:22,182
Unstable?

650
00:53:23,182 --> 00:53:26,182
Dylan's not unstable.
He's just upset.

651
00:53:26,302 --> 00:53:28,742
We'll run a battery of tests
and know in a few days.

652
00:53:28,862 --> 00:53:31,142
Does he have to stay overnight?

653
00:53:31,262 --> 00:53:32,582
Absolutely.

654
00:53:38,942 --> 00:53:41,542
Anything more happen
we need to know about?

655
00:53:43,422 --> 00:53:44,382
Like what?

656
00:53:45,182 --> 00:53:48,782
Sometimes what a child
says or fantasizes...

657
00:53:48,902 --> 00:53:50,982
will give a clue
to what ails him.

658
00:53:51,102 --> 00:53:54,582
Did he say anything
while he was still lucid?

659
00:54:10,702 --> 00:54:12,302
What do we have here?

660
00:54:12,422 --> 00:54:14,782
Too soon to know for sure.

661
00:54:14,902 --> 00:54:17,942
The early symptoms point
to childhood schizophrenia.

662
00:54:21,982 --> 00:54:24,222
Dylan, can you hear me?

663
00:54:26,542 --> 00:54:30,182
Dylan, you have to fight it,
whatever is after you...

664
00:54:30,302 --> 00:54:31,982
and you got to come back to me.

665
00:54:35,000 --> 00:54:40,000
Upcoming jump scare (Major)
You can't make it alone.
Do you hear?
If you can hear me, tell me
what you need to feel safe.

666
00:54:47,702 --> 00:54:49,982
Rex? Is that what you want?

667
00:54:52,222 --> 00:54:56,902
Well, Rex is at home,
and that's where you should be.

668
00:54:57,022 --> 00:55:00,422
But you got to get better before
they'll let you come home.

669
00:55:00,542 --> 00:55:01,662
Do you understand?

670
00:55:03,022 --> 00:55:04,982
Home.

671
00:55:05,102 --> 00:55:07,702
Home. Home, that's right.

672
00:55:07,822 --> 00:55:09,982
That's where I want you,
sweetie.

673
00:55:10,102 --> 00:55:12,862
And, you know,
we're not that far away.

674
00:55:12,982 --> 00:55:15,822
Look right out there.

675
00:55:15,942 --> 00:55:19,022
Past the freeway is our home.

676
00:55:19,142 --> 00:55:23,942
But to get there, you have to
come out from where you are...

677
00:55:24,062 --> 00:55:27,662
so that they'll let you
come home to Rex.

678
00:55:27,782 --> 00:55:29,062
And to me.

679
00:55:30,862 --> 00:55:32,342
Time for your medicine, cowboy.

680
00:55:33,502 --> 00:55:36,422
- Here you go.
- What is that?

681
00:55:36,542 --> 00:55:38,422
Something to help him sleep.

682
00:55:41,902 --> 00:55:44,822
There you go. It looks good.

683
00:55:50,182 --> 00:55:51,622
There you go.

684
00:55:54,822 --> 00:55:57,182
Good. Good. Attaboy.

685
00:55:57,302 --> 00:55:59,222
Come on,
lie down and take a little nap.

686
00:55:59,342 --> 00:56:01,062
You should get some rest, too.

687
00:56:01,182 --> 00:56:03,342
He's going to be fine.
We're gonna do some tests...

688
00:56:03,462 --> 00:56:04,902
and then
you can come back later.

689
00:56:06,302 --> 00:56:08,862
Can you get
that other side, please?

690
00:56:08,982 --> 00:56:10,782
I grabbed his things.

691
00:56:10,902 --> 00:56:12,942
These are
his favourite pyjamas here.

692
00:56:16,462 --> 00:56:18,262
Honey, I've got to go.

693
00:56:18,382 --> 00:56:19,502
I love you, Dylan.

694
00:56:20,542 --> 00:56:22,062
Remember what I said.

695
00:56:24,022 --> 00:56:25,702
We'll take care of everything.

696
00:57:18,062 --> 00:57:19,462
Wake up, lady!

697
00:57:22,742 --> 00:57:24,142
Don't lose it now!

698
00:57:40,062 --> 00:57:41,542
Seismologists at Cal Tech...

699
00:57:41,702 --> 00:57:43,902
have counted
over 300 temblors so far.

700
00:57:44,062 --> 00:57:46,142
Though most were too faint
for us to feel...

701
00:57:46,302 --> 00:57:48,942
seven have shaken our community
in the last few weeks...

702
00:57:49,102 --> 00:57:50,982
and now scientists
are speculating...

703
00:57:51,142 --> 00:57:54,022
there might be an unknown fault
running beneath Los Angeles...

704
00:57:54,182 --> 00:57:55,302
a fault that could...

705
00:58:05,302 --> 00:58:07,662
Hi. You've reached
the Englund residence.

706
00:58:07,822 --> 00:58:09,022
We're out of town.

707
00:58:09,182 --> 00:58:11,382
You can leave a message
if you wish, but...

708
00:58:11,542 --> 00:58:13,742
we'll be gone for some time.

709
00:58:37,622 --> 00:58:39,422
I wish I could tell you
where the script was going.

710
00:58:39,542 --> 00:58:40,862
The fact is I don't know.

711
00:58:40,982 --> 00:58:45,022
I dream a scene at night,
I write it down in the morning.

712
00:58:45,142 --> 00:58:47,422
Beyond that, your guess is as
good as mine where it's going.

713
00:58:47,582 --> 00:58:49,702
At least tell me
what it's about so far.

714
00:58:51,382 --> 00:58:53,182
- Coffee.
- Thanks.

715
00:58:53,302 --> 00:58:56,022
I can tell you what
the nightmare's about so far.

716
00:58:56,142 --> 00:59:00,102
It's about this entity...
whatever you want to call it.

717
00:59:00,222 --> 00:59:02,782
It's old. It's very old.

718
00:59:02,902 --> 00:59:06,262
It's existed in different forms
in different times.

719
00:59:06,382 --> 00:59:09,182
The only thing that stays
the same is what it lives for.

720
00:59:09,342 --> 00:59:10,822
What is that?

721
00:59:10,982 --> 00:59:12,702
The murder of innocents.

722
00:59:13,902 --> 00:59:17,262
This is still a script
we're talking about, right, Wes?

723
00:59:18,902 --> 00:59:22,742
I sort of think of it
as a nightmare in progress.

724
00:59:22,862 --> 00:59:24,502
In this nightmare in progress...

725
00:59:24,622 --> 00:59:26,422
does this thing
have any weaknesses?

726
00:59:26,582 --> 00:59:28,542
It can be captured sometimes.

727
00:59:28,662 --> 00:59:30,782
Captured? How?

728
00:59:30,902 --> 00:59:32,782
By storytellers, of all things.

729
00:59:33,702 --> 00:59:36,502
Every so often, they imagine
a story good enough...

730
00:59:36,662 --> 00:59:38,462
to sort of catch its essence.

731
00:59:38,622 --> 00:59:41,422
Then, for a while,
it's held prisoner in the story.

732
00:59:41,542 --> 00:59:45,502
- Like the genie in the bottle.
- Exactly.

733
00:59:45,622 --> 00:59:47,662
But the problem comes
when the story dies.

734
00:59:47,782 --> 00:59:48,982
And that can happen
in a lot of ways.

735
00:59:49,142 --> 00:59:50,662
It can get too familiar...

736
00:59:50,782 --> 00:59:53,542
or somebody waters it down
to make it an easier sell...

737
00:59:53,662 --> 00:59:58,022
or maybe it's so upsetting
that it's banned outright.

738
00:59:58,142 --> 01:00:00,502
However it happens,
when the story dies...

739
01:00:00,662 --> 01:00:02,622
the evil is set free.

740
01:00:02,742 --> 01:00:06,622
You're saying Freddy
is this ancient thing?

741
01:00:06,742 --> 01:00:09,382
Right. The current version.

742
01:00:09,502 --> 01:00:12,702
And for ten years, he's been
held captive as Freddy...

743
01:00:12,822 --> 01:00:15,702
in the "Nightmare on Elm Street"
series, but...

744
01:00:15,822 --> 01:00:19,942
now that the films have ended,
the genie's out of the bottle.

745
01:00:20,062 --> 01:00:23,742
That's what the nightmares
are telling me and I'm writing.

746
01:00:23,902 --> 01:00:28,382
If Freddy's loose in
your script, where's he going?

747
01:00:28,502 --> 01:00:30,942
Another age? Another form?

748
01:00:31,102 --> 01:00:34,262
No, that's not what
the dreams have him doing.

749
01:00:34,382 --> 01:00:35,662
What is he doing?

750
01:00:36,902 --> 01:00:39,062
He's sort of gotten used
to being Freddy now...

751
01:00:39,182 --> 01:00:41,542
and he likes
our time and space...

752
01:00:41,702 --> 01:00:46,182
so he's decided to cross over
out of films into our reality.

753
01:00:50,262 --> 01:00:52,382
Isn't there somebody
who can stop him?

754
01:00:52,502 --> 01:00:55,782
Actually there is a person
in the dream...

755
01:00:55,902 --> 01:00:58,142
sort of a gatekeeper,
so to speak.

756
01:00:58,262 --> 01:01:00,702
Somebody Freddy has to get by...

757
01:01:00,862 --> 01:01:03,902
before he can
come into our world.

758
01:01:04,022 --> 01:01:06,542
That person's you, Heather.

759
01:01:06,662 --> 01:01:07,862
It's me?

760
01:01:09,782 --> 01:01:10,942
Why me?

761
01:01:11,062 --> 01:01:13,582
Dramatically speaking,
it makes perfect sense.

762
01:01:13,702 --> 01:01:15,182
You played Nancy, after all.

763
01:01:15,302 --> 01:01:17,422
You were the first
to humiliate him, defeat him.

764
01:01:17,542 --> 01:01:20,062
That was Nancy. Not me.

765
01:01:20,182 --> 01:01:22,942
